---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import CompactionProjectionKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/CompactionProjectionKeystone.astro";
import CheckpointSchema from "../../../components/diagrams/CheckpointSchema.astro";
import PriorMessagesPipeline from "../../../components/diagrams/PriorMessagesPipeline.astro";
import SummarizerAuthority from "../../../components/diagrams/SummarizerAuthority.astro";
import CompactKindsFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/CompactKindsFlow.astro";
import HighWaterCompactFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/HighWaterCompactFlow.astro";
import RollingCheckpointFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/RollingCheckpointFlow.astro";
import MidTurnHeadAnchorFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/MidTurnHeadAnchorFlow.astro";
import ShapingVsVerdictFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ShapingVsVerdictFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="03" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      Context windows fill; “remember everything” is a fantasy. Compaction lets the model lawfully
      forget older turns while historical facts remain recoverable from the log / evidence layer —
      what is forgotten is a projection, not the world. Key line:
      <strong>compaction is the Events Log's projection.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§03 · Scene"
    title="Start from a long-running session"
    lede="Full history still has value; the next call cannot and should not re-stuff thousands of facts into the prompt."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user and Maka work for two hours: reading a project, emitting huge test output,
      editing files, debating a wrong direction and rolling back, finishing a first fix, then asking
      for the next failing case. The full Runtime Events Log may hold thousands of facts — exact
      commands, tool results seen at the time, user constraints, a clue that becomes useful again
      later — all still true history.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the next model call usually needs only: current goal, done vs in-progress, irreversible
      decisions, current files and run state, next steps, and where to fetch originals when a summary
      is not enough. The most dangerous implementation conflates “need to keep working” with “need to
      keep truth”: generate a summary, then delete or overwrite the original events. If the model
      drops one constraint, the system has no stable source left to correct it.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      The question is not “how to make the chat shorter,” but: how do you compute a smaller
      continuation view for the next model decision while keeping the full event facts? Continuation
      view ≠ deleting facts.
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§03 · Keystone"
    title="Compaction is not mutation — it is projection"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; fixed system is NewsLiquid tokens, hand keystones, and motion discipline."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Source log immutable: project into a durable checkpoint, materialize with raw tail into this provider request; the same log remains replayable."
      alt="Runtime Events Log fans into HistoryCompactCheckpoint and recent raw Events tail; Materialize feeds a dashed Provider request; invariant: Compaction projects the log and never mutates canonical RuntimeEvents."
    >
      <CompactionProjectionKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p class="figure-note">
      In database terms, a checkpoint is closer to a materialized view than WAL truncation — it can be
      invalidated and rebuilt; it must not declare that the source log no longer matters.
    </p>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Projection relation">Canonical history = RuntimeEvents[0..n]

Compact checkpoint = Project(
  RuntimeEvents[0..k],
  compaction policy,
  summarizer
)

Next model context = Materialize(
  compact checkpoint,
  RuntimeEvents[k+1..n],
  provider capabilities,
  current context budget
)</pre>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="three-layers"
    label="§03 · Layers"
    title="Three non-interchangeable objects"
    lede="A summary is only text; a safe compaction projection must also bind coverage."
  >
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three objects" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Object</th>
            <th scope="col">Holds</th>
            <th scope="col">Source of truth?</th>
            <th scope="col">May lose detail?</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Runtime Events Log</td>
            <td>Semantic facts already produced by user / model / tools / Runtime</td>
            <td>Yes · canonical</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>HistoryCompactCheckpoint</td>
            <td>Continuation summary + coverage for a verified prefix</td>
            <td>No · durable projection</td>
            <td>Yes (lossy)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Provider Request Messages</td>
            <td>Working context this LLM call actually consumes</td>
            <td>No · ephemeral projection</td>
            <td>Yes (recomputable)</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      A checkpoint ≈ a materialized view, not WAL truncation. Summary text is content;
      <strong>coverage</strong> is eligibility to replace a prefix. A bare string cannot answer: which
      Session, how many ordered RuntimeEvents / Turns, which ending
      <code>runId / turnId / runtimeEventId</code>, what source digest, whether it is a legal successor,
      and whether current token policy still admits it into the prompt.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="schema"
    label="§03 · Schema"
    title="HistoryCompactCheckpoint conceptual schema"
    lede="Field groups for teaching — do not freeze TypeScript as product API; digest ≠ natural-language correctness."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Five field groups: identity / high water / coverage / projection / lineage; sourceDigest loops back to the covered prefix."
      alt="Source-log strip and five field-group boxes; digest loop from coverage back to the ordered RuntimeEvents prefix."
    >
      <CheckpointSchema />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="HistoryCompactCheckpoint conceptual schema">HistoryCompactCheckpoint
  identity
    checkpointId, sessionId, createdAt
  high water
    highWaterName, highWaterSeq
  coverage
    eventCount, turnCount
    through {'{'} runId, turnId, runtimeEventId {'}'}
    sourceDigest          # SHA-256 of stable-serialized covered prefix
  projection
    summary, limitations, estimatedTokens
  lineage
    previousCheckpointId?
  phase?                  # absent | pre_turn | mid_turn (absent ≡ pre_turn)
  headAnchor?             # required for mid_turn: { runtimeEventId, turnId }
  source?                 # evidence-spine: runtime_event_projection cursors</pre>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="What field groups prove" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Field group</th>
            <th scope="col">What it proves</th>
            <th scope="col">What it does not prove</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>coverage.through</code> + counts</td>
            <td>Which ordered prefix is claimed</td>
            <td>Summary completeness</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>sourceDigest</code></td>
            <td>Same bytes of source events as when built</td>
            <td>Natural-language accuracy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>phase</code> / <code>headAnchor</code></td>
            <td>Whether the fold reached into the active turn; which user event is re-rendered verbatim</td>
            <td>That the turn is finished; that the summary “remembers” that prompt</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>lineage</code></td>
            <td>Legal successor / same-coverage CAS rewrite</td>
            <td>That older raw events were deleted</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>limitations</code></td>
            <td>Replay-time honesty to the model</td>
            <td>Authority upgrade</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      Prefix-match gate (mental model of <code>matchHistoryCompactCheckpointPrefix</code>): (1) event
      count sufficient; (2) last <code>runId / turnId / runtimeEventId</code> matches; (3) digest exact;
      (4) if <code>phase: mid_turn</code>, the headAnchor must still be the
      <strong>user event of <code>coverage.through</code>’s turn</strong>. Any miss →
      <code>coverage_miss</code> / <code>source_hash_mismatch</code> diagnostics;
      <strong>no fuzzy reuse</strong>. A checkpoint ID only names a projection; source coverage binds it
      to the canonical log.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="mid-turn"
    label="§03 · Mid-turn"
    title="mid_turn: prefix digest reaches into the active turn; headAnchor replays verbatim"
    lede="Coverage stays an ordered prefix; the projection re-inserts the current turn’s user message into the model view after the lossy block."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2b · mid_turn: covered prefix (includes headAnchor) → validate “compacted turn’s user” → replay [block, verbatim anchor, tail]."
      alt="Three columns: covered prefix includes headAnchor; headAnchor must be lastCovered.turn’s user; replay is block+anchor+tail."
    >
      <MidTurnHeadAnchorFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Turn-boundary compaction (<code>pre_turn</code>, also the legacy default) folds a completed prefix
      <em>before</em> the current turn. A long single turn can pile completed steps
      <strong>inside</strong> that turn — V2 then allows <code>phase: mid_turn</code>: coverage reaches into
      those completed steps, but the projection must not let the current prompt vanish into a lossy
      summary. Protocol: coverage <strong>still includes</strong> the head-anchor user event (digest math
      requires a contiguous prefix); replay <strong>re-inserts</strong> it verbatim after the synthetic
      compact block:
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="mid_turn replay shape">pre_turn  → [synthetic compact block, …uncoveredTail]
mid_turn  → [synthetic compact block, verbatim headAnchor, …uncoveredTail]</pre>

    <h3 class="subhead">The headAnchor subtlety</h3>
    <p>
      The anchor must be the <strong>compacted turn’s user event</strong> — on
      <code>lastCovered.turnId</code>, with <code>role=user</code> / <code>author=user</code>. “Any covered
      user” is not enough: pointing at a <strong>prior turn’s</strong> user can look self-consistent yet
      silently drop the real current prompt on replay — so build and match both
      <strong>fail closed</strong> here.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="mid_turn fail-closed" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table proto-table--fail">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Gate</th>
            <th scope="col">Reject when (excerpt)</th>
            <th scope="col">Result</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Build</td>
            <td>Empty coverage / mixed session / any partial / blank summary / mid_turn without anchor / anchor not compacted-turn user</td>
            <td>Throw — no candidate</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Match</td>
            <td>Count/through/session/source cursor miss; digest mismatch; mid_turn anchor corrupt or wrong turn</td>
            <td>
              <code>coverage_miss</code> / <code>source_hash_mismatch</code> — zero coverage, no fuzzy reuse
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Replace</td>
            <td>Not forward progress; equal count without explicit same-coverage CAS successor; source-bound tip replaced by sourceless legacy</td>
            <td>Refuse replace</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      <code>sourceDigest</code> is a length-prefixed <code>stableStringify</code> SHA-256 stream over covered
      events (teach “byte identity”; do not memorize serialization). Evidence-spine Phase 2C additionally
      binds <code>source.kind = runtime_event_projection</code> and policy
      <code>maka.compactable_runtime_event_projection.v1</code>: Compaction eats the session/model-context
      projection, not “one AgentRun’s append log”. Legacy V2 without <code>source</code> stays readable; a
      source-bound tip must not hide behind a legacy record that cannot prove cursor semantics.
    </p>
    <p>
      <code>checkpointId</code> hashes phase/anchor <strong>only when set</strong> — so absent vs explicit
      <code>pre_turn</code> keep the same id; a <code>mid_turn</code> over the same coverage is a distinct
      identity. Specimens: <code>history-compact-checkpoint.ts</code> ·
      <code>history-compact-mid-turn-checkpoint.test.ts</code>.
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        V2 ledger checkpoint:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/729")}>maka:pr:729</a>. mid_turn + headAnchor path:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/996")}>maka:pr:996</a>; protocol reland after snapshot
        squash:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1014")}>maka:pr:1014</a>. Capacity shaping vs final verdict
        is the next section.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="pipeline"
    label="§03 · Pipeline"
    title="The buildPriorMessages projection pipeline"
    lede="Ordinary Send rebuilds prior history from RuntimeEvents — it does not reuse last call’s provider messages."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Ten-step pipeline: highlight 04 stale prune, 07 LLM rolling, 08 synthetic; 09 dashed optional."
      alt="Two-column numbered steps 01–10 for buildPriorMessages; footer landing truths that compaction lives only in model-history projection."
    >
      <PriorMessagesPipeline />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Exclude current <code>turnId</code> → prior Runtime context;</li>
      <li>Prepare context-budget policy;</li>
      <li>Load newest V2 checkpoint; V1 blocks only as fallback;</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Stale</strong> oversized tool-result prune (pointer to
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/02-evidence-before-compression")}>§02</a>; do not re-teach
        archive protocol here);
      </li>
      <li>Compute high water + retained raw Turn tail;</li>
      <li>Validate checkpoint against source prefix (counts / through / digest);</li>
      <li>If fold needed → LLM rolling successor;</li>
      <li>Materialize checkpoint as a <strong>synthetic</strong> RuntimeEvent + uncovered raw suffix;</li>
      <li>Optional history search / archive retrieval / synthesis cache (dashed step);</li>
      <li>Build provider replay plan → <code>ModelMessage[]</code>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Two landing truths: Compaction lives in <strong>model-history projection</strong>, not in the
      RuntimeEvent append path. A checkpoint is not yet a provider message — it still passes replay
      planning and capability gates.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="synthetic"
    label="§03 · Synthetic"
    title="How a checkpoint enters model history"
    lede="Synthetic exists only in the current projection; it must not be appended back as an original interaction event."
  >
    <p>
      At materialization time the checkpoint typically appears as a continuation envelope: teach the
      intent as <code>role=user</code>, <code>author=system</code> (no XML dump here). It lives only in
      this projection. Durable acceptance of a new V2 checkpoint is a separate operational fact:
      <code>history_compact_checkpoint_recorded</code> on the AgentRun ledger — the system accepted this
      projection; that is not the same as writing it into the covered source.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three objects and ledgers" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Object</th>
            <th scope="col">Ledger</th>
            <th scope="col">Meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Covered RuntimeEvents</td>
            <td>RuntimeEventStore</td>
            <td>Canonical interaction facts</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>history_compact_checkpoint_recorded</code></td>
            <td>AgentRunStore</td>
            <td>System accepted this projection</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Synthetic checkpoint event</td>
            <td>Ephemeral projection</td>
            <td>What the model sees this request</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="high-water"
    label="§03 · Trigger"
    title="High water decides whether to project"
    lede="Stable trigger semantics: past water → fold older prefix → keep raw tail → accept only if checkpoint+tail still fit."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · High-water fold: LLM generates summary value only; default token numbers are Current policy, not protocol constants."
      alt="Five-step pipeline: Past high water, LLM summary, Durable append, Coverage gate, Replay + raw tail."
    >
      <HighWaterCompactFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Automatic history compaction is driven by <code>ContextBudgetPolicy</code>: compute a
      prior-history budget from the model context window; when compactable history crosses high water,
      fold an older prefix while keeping a bounded raw tail. Current default magnitudes (history
      reserve, highWaterRatio, max checkpoint tokens, …) are env- / metadata-overridable — teaching
      nails the semantics, not the numbers.
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Tail selects whole Turns newest-first (do not split ordinary tool call/result pairs).</li>
      <li>
        Giant newest Turn over budget → keep the newest complete function call/response pair; else last
        event.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>minRecentTurns</code> is aspiration; <strong>token cap wins</strong> — never use “at least
        N turns” to blow the context ceiling.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="llm-role"
    label="§03 · Authority"
    title="LLM writes the summary; Runtime owns authority"
    lede="LLM generates value; Runtime owns authority."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Failed tests then a green re-run: the summary may say “tests are green” — still a lossy view; official pass/fail lives in tool results / verifier / terminal (§05)."
      alt="Two columns: LLM summarizer produces continuation prose; Runtime decides coverage, digest, durability, and replay."
    >
      <SummarizerAuthority />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="LLM vs Runtime permissions" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Actor</th>
            <th scope="col">Allowed</th>
            <th scope="col">Forbidden</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>LLM summarizer</td>
            <td>Produce Goal / Done / Decisions / Next / Critical Context text</td>
            <td>Decide coverage, digest, durability, whether the checkpoint may replace a prefix</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Runtime</td>
            <td>
              Select fold prefix &amp; tail; compute digest; durable-append gate; current-policy replay
              gate
            </td>
            <td>Treat a summary sentence as verifier / terminal authority</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>The summary may say tests passed — still a <strong>lossy view</strong> of source events.</li>
      <li>Official pass/fail remains in tool results / verifier / terminal facts (see §05).</li>
      <li>If the digest mismatches, Runtime discards the checkpoint even if the prose looks right.</li>
    </ol>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="rolling"
    label="§03 · Rolling"
    title="Rolling checkpoint: do not re-summarize the world"
    lede="Long sessions cross high water many times; re-folding everything from scratch is expensive and rewrites old facts."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · Rolling: summarizer sees prior S + Δ only; recompute full-prefix coverage; durable-append diamond before same-request replacement."
      alt="Checkpoint N and Newly folded through Summarizer and Recompute cover into a durable-append diamond; failure discards the candidate."
    >
      <RollingCheckpointFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Rolling checkpoint">Checkpoint N+1 = S(Checkpoint N.summary, newly folded events)
coverage = full prefix [0..m]
previousCheckpointId = N
sourceDigest recomputed over full covered prefix</pre>
    <p>
      <strong>Durable-before-replace:</strong> a candidate enters the same-request provider view only
      after <code>history_compact_checkpoint_recorded</code> append succeeds. Same-coverage rewrite
      requires an explicit successor (<code>previousCheckpointId</code>) plus identical digest /
      through / counts — CAS, not silent overwrite. The bounded AgentRun projection updates
      <em>after</em> the canonical append; append fail ⇒ projection must not keep the candidate;
      projection fail ⇒ cold start recovers from ledgers.
    </p>
    <p>
      Coverage must be an <strong>ordered prefix</strong>, not a search summary over an arbitrary event
      set. Prefix constraints make replay <code>checkpoint + uncovered raw suffix</code>, keep high
      water monotonically comparable, and make newly folded events explicit for rolling.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="fail"
    label="§03 · Fail-open"
    title="Fail-open and the failure matrix"
    lede="Fail open to a safe source-derived context, not to an invented summary."
  >
    <p>
      Reader quiz: the rolling summarizer fails after newly evicted events already exist — what happens?
      Answer pattern: reuse an old matching checkpoint + as much raw Turn tail as fits;
      <strong>never</strong> let the old summary claim coverage over newly folded events.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Compaction failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table proto-table--fail">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Failure</th>
            <th scope="col">Current behavior</th>
            <th scope="col">Must not happen</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Below high water</td>
            <td>No invented early summary</td>
            <td>Premature unscoped summary</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Empty LLM summary</td>
            <td>No new checkpoint; first compact → safe raw tail + visible fail-open note</td>
            <td>Empty projection as covered history</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Rolling summarizer fail</td>
            <td>Reuse old checkpoint if still valid; append fittable raw Turns</td>
            <td>Old summary claims new events</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Durable append fail</td>
            <td>Discard candidate; fallback</td>
            <td>Undurable projection in the model then a “recoverable” claim</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Prefix / digest mismatch</td>
            <td>Reject checkpoint</td>
            <td>Approximate match</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Over current budget</td>
            <td>Skip replay of that checkpoint</td>
            <td>Bypass because “it worked yesterday”</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Bounded projection corrupt</td>
            <td>Rescan AgentRun ledgers; repair best-effort</td>
            <td>Cache as sole truth</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>User abort manual compact</td>
            <td>Abort summarizer/write; no next-Turn poison</td>
            <td>Late write reuses abort state</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="v1-v2"
    label="§03 · Compatibility"
    title="V1 block vs V2 ledger"
    lede="V2 is the Current preferred path; V1 remains an honest read-only compatibility fallback — not legacy we pretend is gone."
  >
    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="V1 vs V2" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col"></th>
            <th scope="col">V1 <code>HistoryCompactBlock</code></th>
            <th scope="col">V2 <code>HistoryCompactCheckpoint</code></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Provenance</td>
            <td>Per-event <code>sourceRefs</code> (+ artifacts)</td>
            <td>Prefix metadata + digest over ledger</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Size</td>
            <td>Can grow with event count (MB-class)</td>
            <td>Bounded checkpoint identity</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Current role</td>
            <td>Read-only compatibility fallback</td>
            <td>Preferred main path</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Cleanup</td>
            <td>Reclaim when V2 covers the same prefix</td>
            <td>—</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Reclaim-only cleanup failures must not break replay — honesty beats a tidy-looking cleanup.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="kinds"
    label="§03 · Boundaries"
    title="Do not collapse three compacts into one feature"
    lede="All shrink provider messages; source, lifecycle, and durability strength differ."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 7 · History LLM compaction (this chapter) ≠ Active prune (§02) ≠ semanticCompact — contrast durable acceptance and fail-open posture."
      alt="Three-column contrast: History LLM compaction, Active Tool Result Prune, semanticCompact attention shaping; footer emphasizes fail-open differences."
    >
      <CompactKindsFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Durability of three compact kinds" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Mechanism</th>
            <th scope="col">Durable acceptance</th>
            <th scope="col">Fail-open posture</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>History LLM compaction</td>
            <td>Must durable-append before accepted replacement</td>
            <td>Safe raw / old checkpoint; no false coverage</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Active tool-result prune (§02)</td>
            <td>Archive before placeholder; ledger untouched</td>
            <td>Keep full provider message</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>semanticCompact</code></td>
            <td>Best-effort diagnostic block; invocation-local</td>
            <td>
              Signed savings / cache miss are diagnostics, not hard reject; head/protocol gates stay hard
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>
      Do not call all three “summary.” Mid-turn capacity protocol depth lives in
      <a href="#mid-turn">#mid-turn</a> and <a href="#capacity-shaping">#capacity-shaping</a>. Unifying
      “all LLM compacts share one durable coverage contract” for <code>semanticCompact</code> remains a
      Target direction, not Current. Reactive overflow compact-and-retry is an adjacent mechanism (
      <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1017")}>maka:pr:1017</a>), not the shaping/verdict split
      itself.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="capacity-shaping"
    label="§03 · Capacity"
    title="Mid-turn capacity: shaping ≠ final-request verdict"
    lede="The shaper only selects a safe prefix and builds a mid_turn checkpoint (fail-open); pass/terminate belongs solely to the backend’s final estimate of the real outgoing payload."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 7b · Left: shaper (skip / fail_open / compacted); right: backend final-request estimate (continue / context_budget_exhausted)."
      alt="Two swimlanes: mid-turn-capacity-compact must not issue context_budget_exhausted; backend measures outgoing payload after all shaping."
    >
      <ShapingVsVerdictFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      The module doc-comment is authority (no upstream architecture draft):
      <code>mid-turn-capacity-compact.ts</code> is a <strong>pure measurement + safe-boundary engine</strong>
      — turn-agnostic and side-effect free. It only <strong>SHAPES</strong>: select the largest safe
      covered prefix, build the checkpoint and replacement projection; fail open when it cannot. The
      safety-critical pass/terminate is <strong>not issued here</strong> — the backend’s final-request
      estimate owner measures the actual outgoing <code>(messages, tools)</code> after
      <strong>every</strong> shaping hook (including this fold and prune) and then decides
      <code>context_budget_exhausted</code>. The verdict is always about the
      <strong>request that really goes out</strong>, never a second guess over the pre-fold raw ledger.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="shaping vs verdict" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Layer</th>
            <th scope="col">May say</th>
            <th scope="col">Must not say</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Shaper (<code>planMidTurnCapacityCompaction</code>)</td>
            <td><code>skip</code> / <code>fail_open</code> / <code>compacted</code></td>
            <td><code>context_budget_exhausted</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Backend final-request estimate</td>
            <td>continue / <code>context_budget_exhausted</code></td>
            <td>Treat a raw-ledger re-estimate as the outgoing payload; accept a non-shrinking fold</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="subhead">Safe boundary (fail-closed cut)</h3>
    <p>
      <code>selectMidTurnSafeBoundary</code> picks the largest contiguous <code>coveredCount</code> such
      that:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        The cut ends on an immutable, non-<code>partial</code> event; any partial in the pool retreats
        the max cut to before the first partial.
      </li>
      <li>
        It <strong>never straddles</strong> a tool call/result pair (a provider protocol unit). An open
        call with no response yet: any cut past the call is unsafe.
      </li>
      <li>It leaves at least <code>reserveTailEvents</code> as a verbatim tail (planner default 1).</li>
      <li>
        It pins current-turn <code>steering: true</code> text — the injection accumulator re-appends live
        directives on every request of the send; covering them only desynchronizes capacity measurement
        from the real outgoing payload.
      </li>
      <li>
        Coverage must include the headAnchor and at least one other event (folding only the anchor saves
        nothing — it is re-rendered verbatim).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      No safe cut → shaper <code>fail_open</code> (<code>no_safe_completed_span</code>), not a provider
      error. The window may still be explicitly exhausted later by the backend’s final estimate.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Trigger measurement and why the shaper skips a post-fold verdict</h3>
    <p>
      The trigger anchors on the last request’s real <strong>INPUT</strong> tokens (not input+output)
      plus a signed char/4 delta; a negative delta <strong>credits shrink</strong> after
      compaction/prune. Cold start (no usable input sample) falls back to a whole-payload char estimate —
      covering the full provider input including the system prompt. The shaper
      <strong>deliberately</strong> issues no post-fold window verdict over the raw ledger: if the prior
      request was itself a compacted projection, the raw covered span was never in that request —
      subtracting it would over-credit. The backend applies the shape only when the materialized
      replacement <strong>actually shrinks</strong> the outgoing payload, then the final-request owner
      re-measures — a runaway summary is refused (<code>failedOpen</code>), not carried forward.
    </p>
    <p>
      Specimen tests: <code>mid-turn-capacity-compact.test.ts</code> (including “still shapes when the
      estimate exceeds the window — no post-fold window verdict here”);
      <code>mid-turn-capacity-backend.test.ts</code> (verdict after prune, load_tools schema growth, INPUT
      baseline, volatile turn tail, default-on guards).
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        The title names the invariant:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/996")}>maka:pr:996</a>
        (mid-turn capacity compaction with a single final-payload verdict owner). Protocol reland:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1014")}>maka:pr:1014</a>. Reactive overflow
        compact-and-retry (adjacent):
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/1017")}>maka:pr:1017</a>. Outgoing request shape / tool
        schema churn →
        <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#request-shape"}
          >§01 · request-shape</a
        >.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="cache-pointer"
    label="§03 · Cache pointer"
    title="Folding history changes request shape"
    lede="One causal sentence + pointer; full cache / prefixHash teaching is not this chapter."
  >
    <p>
      Folding or replacing a history prefix changes <code>historyProjectionHash</code> — often with
      <code>requestShapeChangeReason = history_projection_changed</code> while <code>prefixHash</code>
      may stay stable. Shorter history ≠ cheaper if cache miss rises. Full attribution ladder,
      <code>prefixHash</code> non-goals, tool-schema economy →
      <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#request-shape"}
        >§01 · request-shape</a
      >
      (map #34 · #38 teaching plan). This chapter nails the causal link only — it does not rewrite the
      full request-shape essay.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="invariants"
    label="§03 · Invariants"
    title="Twelve invariants that must hold"
    lede="You should be able to recite these. Do not break them while chasing tokens."
  >
    <ol class="plain-list numbered invariants">
      <li>
        <strong>Source immutability</strong> — Compaction never mutates or deletes canonical
        RuntimeEvents.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Projection coverage</strong> — Ordered prefix + through + digest; missing any ⇒ no
        replacement.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No durability, no replacement</strong> —
        <code>history_compact_checkpoint_recorded</code> must succeed before same-request provider view.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Monotonic high water</strong> — Or an explicit same-coverage successor (CAS); no silent
        overwrite.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Current-policy validation</strong> — Re-validate on every replay; historically legal ≠
        currently usable.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Raw recent tail within budget</strong> — Turn integrity first; token cap beats
        minRecentTurns.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No false coverage on rolling failure</strong> — Fail open to a safe source-derived
        context.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Projection rebuildable</strong> — Rebuild from canonical ledgers; cache is not sole
        truth.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Failure observable</strong> — Diagnostics such as <code>coverage_miss</code> /
        <code>source_hash_mismatch</code> are visible.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Authority preserved</strong> — Summary ≠ verifier / terminal authority upgrade.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>mid_turn headAnchor honesty</strong> — Anchor must be the compacted turn’s user; coverage
        includes it; replay re-inserts it; corruption → fail-closed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Shaping ≠ verdict</strong> — The mid-turn shaper only fails open;
        <code>context_budget_exhausted</code> is issued only by the final-request estimate over the real
        outgoing payload.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="not"
    label="§03 · Not"
    title="What compaction is not"
    lede="Draw the boundary so a summary is never elevated into memory, deletion, or official conclusion."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Not Memory</strong> — Serves current Session continuation, not a cross-Session knowledge
        base.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not deleting history</strong> — Covered events leave this working set, not the canonical
        ledger.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not semantically lossless</strong> — Digest proves which source prefix; it does not prove
        the summary omitted nothing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not bit-exact replay</strong> — Semantic sources are rebuildable; identical summary prose
        is not promised.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not official conclusion</strong> — “Tests passed” in a summary is still a paraphrase;
        authority lives in source / verifier / terminal fact (see §05).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current · V2 preferred · Target honesty</p>
      <p>
        V2 ledger-backed <code>HistoryCompactCheckpoint</code> is the preferred main path; V1
        artifact-backed <code>HistoryCompactBlock</code> remains read-only compatibility. Default token
        thresholds are policy knobs. Summary quality gates / summarizer identity in the manifest =
        Target/future — teaching does not fake-ship them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

